<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<Page
  x:Class="MdcAi.ChatUI.Views.GettingStartedTips.Conversations"
  xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
  xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
  xmlns:local="using:MdcAi.ChatUI.Views.GettingStartedTips"
  xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
  xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
  mc:Ignorable="d">

  <StackPanel Spacing="5">
    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
      Start new conversations for distinct topics. Stick to one task at a time to maintain
      focus and clarity. For instance, debating AI whether tea trumps coffee should be separate
      from exploring milk's compatibility with either. They may seem related but deserve their
      own spotlight.
    </TextBlock>
    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
      This approach sharpens AI precision and conserves
      <Hyperlink NavigateUri="https://help.openai.com/en/articles/4936856-what-are-tokens-and-how-to-count-them">tokens</Hyperlink>
      . Discussing whether milk
      meshes well with tea or coffee is a world apart from the tea vs. coffee affair. Mixing the two
      dilutes the conversation. Remember, GPT AI recalls <Bold>every message</Bold> of the conversation, not
      just the last few exchanges. Every new question sends the whole transcript back through,
      cranking up token costs exponentially.
    </TextBlock>
    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
      <Bold>To summarize:</Bold> focus each conversation, and break down big topics into bite-sized conversations.
    </TextBlock>
  </StackPanel>
</Page>